definition.value: A hydroxy-amino acid that is tryptophan substituted by at least one hydroxy group at unspecified position.
A long-chain fatty acyl-CoA(4-) oxanion arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of 12-methyltridecanoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3
A hydroxy fatty acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any 3-hydroxy fatty acid.
A 3-hydroxy fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-hydroxytetradecanoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A 3-hydroxy fatty acyl-CoA(4-) oxanion arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of 3-hydroxytetradecanoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.

A quinolinemonocarboxylic acid that is quinoline-8-carboxylic acid carrying additional methyl and chloro substituents at positions 3 and 7 respectively. A residual herbicide used to control broad-leaved weeds on a range of crops including cereals, rape and beet.
A hydroxy saturated fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of 12-hydroxyoctadecanoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A long-chain fatty acyl-CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of 12-hydroxyoctadecanoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
An omega-hydroxy-lon-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of 15-hydroxypentadecanoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A fatty acyl-CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of any omega-hydroxy fatty acyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
An omega-hydroxy fatty acyl-CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of 15-hydroxypentadecanoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
A member of the class of furoic acids that is 2-furoic acid substituted at position 5 by a formyl group.
An omega-hydroxy fatty acyl-CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of 16-hydroxyhexadecanoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.

An amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of selenocysteine at the amino group or the carboxy group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of selenocysteine by a heteroatom. The definition normally excludes peptides containing selenocysteine residues.
A proteinogenic amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of L-selenocysteine at the amino group or the carboxy group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of L-selenocysteine by a heteroatom.

A non-proteinogenic amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of D-selenocysteine at the amino group or the carboxy group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of D-selenocysteine by a heteroatom.
A member of the class of furoic acids that is 2-furoic acid substituted at position 5 by a dihydroxymethyl group.
A member of the class of furans carrying two carboxy substituents at positions 2 and 5.
A member of the class of furans that is 2-furfural substituted at position 4 by a phosphooxymethyl group.
An unsaturated fatty acyl-CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of 9-decenoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
An L-glutamine derivative obtained by formal condensation of the side-chain carboxy group of glutamic acid with the amino group of tyramine.
An  epoxide that is oxirane substituted by a methyl and a propyl group at positions 2 and 3 respectively. Metabolite observed in cancer metabolism.
A member of the class of furans that is 2-furylmethylamine substituted at position 4 by a phosphooxymethyl group.
An alkene that is (4E)-dec-4-ene with a methyl group at position 7. Metabolite observed in cancer metabolism.
A nitroalkene that is 1-undecene substituted by a nitro group at position 11.  Metabolite observed in cancer metabolism.
An alkene that is docosane with an unsaturation at position 1. Metabolite observed in cancer metabolism.
A cycloalkane that is cyclohexane substituted by an ethyl and a propyl group at positions 1 and 2 respectively. Metabolite observed in cancer metabolism.
An   iodoalkane that is undecane substituted by an iodo group at position 1 and a methyl group at position 2. Metabolite observed in cancer metabolism.
An alkene that is 1-nonene substituted by methyl groups at positions 4, 6 and 8 respectively. Metabolite observed in cancer metabolism.
A tertiary alcohol that is propan-2-ol substituted by a 4-methoxyphenyl group at position 2. Metabolite observed in cancer metabolism.
A  hexenal that is (3E)-hex-3-enal substituted by methyl groups at positions 2, 3 and 6. Metabolite observed in cancer metabolism.
An alkane that is decane substituted by methyl groups at positions 2, 3, 5 and 8. Metabolite observed in cancer metabolism.
A  diester obtained by the formal condensation of 2,4,4-trimethylpentane-1,3-diol with two molecules of 2-methylpropanoic acid. Metabolite observed in cancer metabolism.
A long-chain alkane that is heptadecane substituted by methyl groups at positions 2, 6, 10 and 14. Metabolite observed in cancer metabolism.
A long-chain alkane that is heptadecane substituted by methyl groups at positions 2, 6, 10 and 15. Metabolite observed in cancer metabolism.
An  alkene that is (3E)-oct-3-ene substituted by methyl groups at positions 2 and 6. Metabolite observed in cancer metabolism.
Any organic heterotricyclic compound constructed from fused thiophene, triazole and diazepeine rings.
A hydroxypolyether that is the monomethyl ether derivative of triethylene glycol. Metabolite observed in cancer metabolism.
A phosphatidylethanolamine 36:1 zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the amino to the phosphate group of 1-oleoyl-2-stearoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine; major species at pH 7.3.
A primary alcohol that is 1-octanol substituted by a butyl group at position 2. Metabolite observed in cancer metabolism.
A primary aliphatic amine that is butan-2-amine substituted by a methyl group at position 2. Metabolite observed in cancer metabolism.
An alkane that is  octane substituted by methyl groups at positions 3 and 5. Metabolite observed in cancer metabolism.
A 1-phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol 3,4,5-trisphosphate in which the phosphatidyl acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are both specified as octanoyl.
A fatty alcohol that is 1-dodecanol substituted by methyl groups at positions 3, 7 and 11. Metabolite observed in cancer metabolism.
A 1-phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol 3,4-bisphosphate in which the phosphatidyl acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are both specified as octanoyl.
A 1-phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol 4,5-bisphosphate in which the phosphatidyl acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are both specified as octanoyl.
